## 5. File-by-File Explanation

---

### [index.html](file:///d:/BB/news/index.html) — The Shell
```html
<div id="root"></div>
<script type="module" src="/src/main.js"></script>
```
- The `div#root` is where React mounts the entire app
- `type="module"` = modern ES module — allows `import/export`
- Vite serves [main.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/main.js) as the entry point

**Viva Q: Why only one HTML file?**
Because this is a **Single Page Application (SPA)**. React handles all routing in JavaScript. The browser never actually navigates to a new page — React swaps out components instead.

---

### [vite.config.js](file:///d:/BB/news/vite.config.js) — Build Tool Config
```js
import { defineConfig } from 'vite'
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react'
import { transform } from 'esbuild'

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [
    {
      name: 'jsx-in-js',
      async transform(code, id) {
        if (id.endsWith('.js') && code.includes('</')) {
          const result = await transform(code, {
            loader: 'jsx',
            jsx: 'automatic',
            jsxImportSource: 'react'
          })
          return result.code
        }
      }
    },
    react()
  ],
  optimizeDeps: {
    esbuildOptions: {
      loader: { '.js': 'jsx' }
    }
  }
})
```
**Why this exists:**  
Normal Vite only processes `.jsx` files as JSX. This project uses [.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/App.js) files with JSX inside them. The custom plugin uses `esbuild`'s [transform()](file:///d:/BB/news/vite.config.js#9-19) to convert [.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/App.js) files that contain JSX (`</` pattern) into valid JavaScript.

**`esbuild`** is an extremely fast JavaScript bundler/transpiler (written in Go). Vite uses it internally.

**`jsx: 'automatic'`** means `import React from 'react'` is NOT needed in every file — React's new JSX transform handles it automatically since React 17.

---

### [package.json](file:///d:/BB/news/package.json) — Project Manifest
```json
"scripts": {
  "dev": "vite",         // Start dev server (hot reload)
  "build": "vite build", // Create production bundle in /dist
  "preview": "vite preview", // Preview the production build locally
  "lint": "eslint . --ext .js",
  "format": "prettier --write \"**/*.{js,css,md,json,cjs}\""
}
```

**dependencies** = needed at runtime (user's browser needs them)
**devDependencies** = only needed during development/build (Vite, ESLint, Prettier)

**Viva Q: Why not include devDeps in deps?**
They'd bloat the production bundle. Users don't need ESLint in their browser.

---

### [src/main.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/main.js) — Application Entry Point
```js
import React from 'react'
import { createRoot } from 'react-dom/client'
import { BrowserRouter } from 'react-router-dom'
import App from './App.js'
import './styles.css'

createRoot(document.getElementById('root')).render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <BrowserRouter>
      <App />
    </BrowserRouter>
  </React.StrictMode>
)
```

| Line | Explanation |
|---|---|
| `createRoot(...)` | React 18 API. Creates a root where React takes control |
| `document.getElementById('root')` | Finds the `<div id="root">` in index.html |
| `.render(...)` | Renders the React tree into that div |
| `React.StrictMode` | Development-only wrapper. Helps catch bugs by double-invoking functions |
| `BrowserRouter` | Enables HTML5 History API routing (clean URLs like `/article/123` instead of `/#/article/123`) |

**Viva Q: Why `BrowserRouter` at the top?**  
All routing hooks (`useNavigate`, `useParams`, `useLocation`) need a router context. Wrapping at the very top ensures every component has access.

---

### [src/theme.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/theme.js) — Theme Factory
```js
import { createTheme } from '@mui/material/styles'

export function getTheme(mode) {
  return createTheme({
    palette: {
      mode: mode || 'light'   // 'light' or 'dark'
    }
  })
}
```
`createTheme` generates a full MUI theme object with colors, spacing, typography. Setting `palette.mode` to `'dark'` flips ALL MUI components to dark automatically.

**Viva Q: Why not just toggle a CSS class?**  
Because MUI components have their own color system. Using `palette.mode` ensures every MUI component (buttons, cards, drawers) correctly switches colors.

---

### [src/styles.css](file:///d:/BB/news/src/styles.css) — Global Reset
```css
* { box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0; padding: 0; }
```
A basic reset so browsers don't add default margins/padding that break layouts.

---

### [src/App.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/App.js) — Root Component (State Hub)

```js
export default function App() {
  const [searchTerm, setSearchTerm] = useState('')
  // Why here? searchTerm is shared between AppBarSearch and NewsList
  
  const [filtersOpen, setFiltersOpen] = useState(false)
  // Why here? AppBarSearch opens the drawer, FiltersDrawer needs to know if it's open
  
  const [sortBy, setSortBy] = useState('latest')
  // Why here? FiltersDrawer sets it, NewsList reads it — they're siblings
  
  const [mode, setMode] = useState('light')
  // Why here? ThemeProvider wraps everything — theme must be at the top
  
  const theme = useMemo(() => getTheme(mode), [mode])
  // useMemo: recalculate ONLY when mode changes, not on every render
```

**Concept: "Lifting state up"**  
When two sibling components need to share data, you move (lift) that state to their closest common parent. Here, [App.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/App.js) is the common parent of [AppBarSearch](file:///d:/BB/news/src/components/AppBarSearch.js#6-65) and [NewsList](file:///d:/BB/news/src/features/news/NewsList.js#36-182), so `searchTerm` lives in [App.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/App.js).

```js
function handleToggleMode() {
  setMode(function(currentMode) {
    return currentMode === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light'
    // Ternary operator: condition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse
  })
}
```
The **functional updater form** of `setState` — you get the guaranteed latest value of the current state. Safer than `setMode(mode === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light')` in async scenarios.

---

### [src/routes/AppRoutes.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/routes/AppRoutes.js) — Router Configuration
```js
export default function AppRoutes(props) {
  const searchTerm = props.searchTerm || ''
  // props.searchTerm || '' means: use props.searchTerm if truthy, else use ''
  // Guard against undefined/null/empty being passed in
```

```js
return (
  <Routes>
    <Route path='/' element={<Home ... />} />
    <Route path='/article/:id' element={<ArticleDetails />} />
  </Routes>
)
```
- [Routes](file:///d:/BB/news/src/routes/AppRoutes.js#6-29) = the container. Only renders the FIRST matching [Route](file:///d:/BB/news/src/routes/AppRoutes.js#6-29)
- `path='/'` = matches the homepage URL
- `path='/article/:id'` = matches any URL like `/article/anything`
- `:id` = **URL parameter** — captured and accessible via `useParams()`

**Viva Q: Why separate AppRoutes from App.js?**  
Single responsibility principle. App.js manages global state. AppRoutes.js manages URL-to-component mapping.

