### [src/features/news/NewsList.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/features/news/NewsList.js) — The Complex Heart

This is the most sophisticated component. It has 3 `useEffect` hooks and 5 state variables.

#### State Variables
```js
const [page, setPage] = useState(0)    // Current API page (0-indexed)
const [items, setItems] = useState([]) // Accumulated article list
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false)  // Show spinner?
const [error, setError] = useState('') // Error message
const [hasMore, setHasMore] = useState(true) // More pages available?
const loadMoreRef = useRef(null) // Reference to the sentinel div at bottom
```

#### Effect 1 — Reset when search/sort changes
```js
React.useEffect(() => {
  setItems([])    // Clear old results
  setPage(0)      // Go back to first page
  setHasMore(true)
}, [query, sortBy])
// Runs whenever query or sortBy changes
// Dependency array = [query, sortBy]
```

#### Effect 2 — Fetch data
```js
React.useEffect(() => {
  let isActive = true  // ← CRITICAL: prevents memory leaks and race conditions

  async function loadNews() {
    setLoading(true)
    setError('')

    try {
      const result = await newsService.search(query || 'news', page, { sortBy })
      
      if (!isActive) return  // Component unmounted? Stop here

      setItems(function(previousItems) {
        const merged = page === 0
          ? result.items           // First page: replace everything
          : previousItems.concat(result.items)  // Later pages: append
        const uniqueItems = uniqueById(merged)  // Remove any duplicates
        return sortItems(uniqueItems, sortBy)   // Apply client-side sort
      })

      setHasMore(result.hasMore)
    } catch (err) {
      if (!isActive) return
      setError(err.message || 'Failed to load news')
    } finally {
      if (isActive) setLoading(false)
    }
  }

  loadNews()

  return () => { isActive = false }  // Cleanup: called on unmount
}, [query, page, sortBy])
```

**Viva Q: Why `isActive`?**  
React components can unmount (be removed from the DOM) while an async request is still in flight. If you call `setState` on an unmounted component, React throws a warning. Setting `isActive = false` in the cleanup prevents that.

**Viva Q: What is `async/await`?**  
A cleaner way to write Promises. `await` pauses execution until the Promise resolves. `async` marks the function as returning a Promise. It makes async code look synchronous.

**Viva Q: What is `try/catch/finally`?**  
- [try](file:///d:/BB/news/src/features/news/NewsList.js#109-115) = run this code
- `catch` = if an error is thrown, handle it here
- `finally` = ALWAYS runs whether success or failure (perfect for `setLoading(false)`)

#### Effect 3 — Infinite Scroll via IntersectionObserver
```js
React.useEffect(() => {
  const currentTarget = loadMoreRef.current
  if (!currentTarget) return

  const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
    entries => {
      const firstEntry = entries[0]
      if (firstEntry && firstEntry.isIntersecting && hasMore && !loading) {
        setPage(currentPage => currentPage + 1)  // Increment page → triggers Effect 2
      }
    },
    { rootMargin: '500px 0px' }  // Trigger 500px BEFORE the element is visible
  )

  observer.observe(currentTarget)

  return () => { observer.disconnect() }  // Cleanup
}, [hasMore, loading])
```

**`IntersectionObserver`** = a browser API that tells you when an element enters/exits the viewport. The sentinel `<Box ref={loadMoreRef} sx={{ height: 20 }} />` at the bottom of the list acts as the trigger.

**`rootMargin: '500px 0px'`** = start loading 500px BEFORE the user actually reaches the bottom. This makes the experience feel seamless — new articles are already loading before you see them.

#### Helper Functions

```js
function uniqueById(list) {
  const map = new Map()  // Map = key-value store, any type as key
  list.forEach(function(item) {
    if (!item || !item.id) return  // Skip invalid items
    map.set(item.id, item)  // If same id, newer value overwrites older
  })
  return Array.from(map.values())  // Convert Map values back to array
}
```
Using a `Map` de-duplicates in O(n) time — much faster than `filter()` with `findIndex()`.

```js
function sortItems(list, sortMode) {
  const sorted = list.slice()  // .slice() with no args = shallow copy (don't mutate original!)
  
  if (sortMode === 'oldest') {
    sorted.sort(function(a, b) {
      return new Date(a.publishedAt).getTime() - new Date(b.publishedAt).getTime()
      // Ascending: smallest date first (oldest)
    })
  }
  
  if (sortMode === 'latest') {
    sorted.sort(function(a, b) {
      return new Date(b.publishedAt).getTime() - new Date(a.publishedAt).getTime()
      // Descending: largest date first (newest)
    })
  }
  // Note: 'relevance' sorting is handled by the API endpoint, not client-side
  return sorted
}
```

**Viva Q: Why `.slice()` before `.sort()`?**  
`.sort()` mutates the original array. If you sort the React state array directly, you might cause unexpected bugs. Always copy first, then sort.

---

### [src/services/newsService.js](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js) — The API Layer

#### Constants
```js
const API_BASE_URL = 'https://hn.algolia.com/api/v1'
// ALL API calls go through this base URL

const PAGE_SIZE = 12
// 12 articles per page. Named constant = easy to change in one place
```

#### [buildUrl(path, params)](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js#15-28) — URL Builder
```js
function buildUrl(path, params = {}) {
  // params = {} means: if no params argument passed, default to empty object
  
  const normalizedBase = API_BASE_URL.endsWith('/') 
    ? API_BASE_URL 
    : `${API_BASE_URL}/`
  // Template literal: `` `${variable}` `` = string interpolation
  
  const normalizedPath = path.startsWith('/') ? path.slice(1) : path
  // Remove leading slash if present (to avoid double slash)
  
  const url = new URL(normalizedPath, normalizedBase)
  // URL constructor: second arg is the base. Handles joining correctly.
  
  Object.entries(params).forEach(function([key, value]) {
    // Object.entries() converts {a: 1, b: 2} to [['a', 1], ['b', 2]]
    // Destructuring: [key, value] unpacks each entry
    
    if (value !== undefined && value !== null && value !== '') {
      url.searchParams.set(key, String(value))
      // .searchParams = the ?key=value part of the URL
    }
  })
  
  return url.toString()
  // Returns: 'https://hn.algolia.com/api/v1/search_by_date?query=ai&tags=story&page=0&hitsPerPage=12'
}
```

#### [fetchJson(path, params)](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js#29-38) — Generic HTTP Fetcher
```js
async function fetchJson(path, params) {
  const response = await fetch(buildUrl(path, params))
  // fetch() = browser's built-in HTTP client. Returns a Promise.
  
  if (!response.ok) {
    // .ok = true if status code is 200-299
    throw new Error('Failed to fetch news data')
  }
  
  return response.json()
  // .json() parses the response body as JSON. Also returns a Promise.
}
```

**Viva Q: Why separate [buildUrl](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js#15-28) and [fetchJson](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js#29-38)?**  
[buildUrl](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js#15-28) is a pure function — testable without the network. [fetchJson](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js#29-38) is reusable for any endpoint. Separation of concerns.

#### HTML Entity Decoder
```js
function decodeHtmlEntities(text) {
  return text
    .replace(/&amp;/gi, '&')
    .replace(/&lt;/gi, '<')
    .replace(/&gt;/gi, '>')
    .replace(/&quot;/gi, '"')
    .replace(/&#39;|&#x27;/gi, "'")
    .replace(/&#x2F;/gi, '/')
    .replace(/&nbsp;/gi, ' ')
}
```
The API returns HTML-encoded text. `&amp;` is the HTML code for `&`. This function converts them back to readable characters.

**Regex explained:** `/&amp;/gi`
- `/` = start pattern
- `&amp;` = the literal string to match
- `/` = end pattern
- `g` = global flag (replace ALL occurrences, not just first)
- `i` = case-insensitive

#### [cleanText(value)](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js#50-64) — HTML Stripper
```js
function cleanText(value) {
  if (!value) return ''
  
  return decodeHtmlEntities(
    String(value)
      .replace(/<\s*br\s*\/?>/gi, '\n')  // <br> → newline
      .replace(/<\/p>/gi, '\n\n')         // </p> → double newline
      .replace(/<[^>]+>/g, ' ')           // Any other HTML tag → space
      .replace(/\s+\n/g, '\n')            // Multiple spaces before newline → one newline
      .replace(/\n{3,}/g, '\n\n')         // 3+ newlines → max 2
      .replace(/[ \t]{2,}/g, ' ')         // Multiple spaces → single space
      .trim()                              // Remove leading/trailing whitespace
  )
}
```

**`<[^>]+>`** — The HTML tag regex:
- `<` = opening angle bracket
- `[^>]+` = one or more characters that are NOT `>`
- `>` = closing angle bracket
- This matches any HTML tag like `<div>`, `<p class="x">`, `<strong>`

#### [getTagFromText()](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js#65-78) — Auto-classification
```js
function getTagFromText(title, description, sourceTags) {
  const haystack = `${title} ${description} ${(sourceTags || []).join(' ')}`.toLowerCase()
  // Combine all text, lowercase it for case-insensitive matching
  
  if (/ai|artificial intelligence|llm|ml|machine learning|gpt/.test(haystack)) return 'ai'
  // .test() returns true/false — does this regex match the haystack?
  // | means OR: match 'ai' OR 'artificial intelligence' OR 'llm' etc.
}
```

**Why this approach?** The API doesn't give us clean categories. We auto-classify by keyword matching. It's not perfect but it's fast and zero-cost.

#### Tag-based SVG Thumbnails
```js
const TAG_COLORS = {
  ai: ['#4527a0', '#283593'],  // [gradientStart, gradientEnd]
  technology: ['#1565c0', '#00838f'],
  ...
}

function getTagThumbnail(tag) {
  const colors = TAG_COLORS[tag] || TAG_COLORS.general
  const label = (tag || 'general').toUpperCase()
  
  const svg = [
    "<svg ...>",
    "<defs><linearGradient ...>",
    `<stop offset='0%' stop-color='${colors[0]}'/>`,
    `<stop offset='100%' stop-color='${colors[1]}'/>`,
    ...
  ].join('')
  
  return `data:image/svg+xml;charset=UTF-8,${encodeURIComponent(svg)}`
  // data URI: embeds the SVG directly as a URL (no server needed)
  // encodeURIComponent() escapes special characters so it's a valid URL
}
```

**Viva Q: Why SVG data URIs instead of real images?**  
The Hacker News API doesn't provide thumbnails. Rather than showing broken image icons, we generate beautiful gradient placeholder images on the fly using SVG, with no network request.

#### Data Mappers
```js
function mapHitToArticle(hit) {
  // 'hit' = Algolia's term for a search result
  const title = cleanText(hit.title || hit.story_title || 'No title')
  // Tries hit.title first, falls back to hit.story_title, falls back to 'No title'
  
  return {
    id: hit.objectID,         // Algolia's unique ID field
    title,                     // Shorthand: same as title: title
    description,
    url: hit.url || hit.story_url || '',
    source: 'Hacker News',
    author: hit.author || 'Unknown author',
    publishedAt: hit.created_at || '',
    tag,
    thumbnailUrl: getTagThumbnail(tag)
  }
}
```

**Why two mappers ([mapHitToArticle](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js#99-116) and [mapItemToArticle](file:///d:/BB/news/src/services/newsService.js#117-134))?**  
The Algolia search API (`/search`) returns "hits" with one field structure. The item detail API (`/items/:id`) returns a single object with a different structure. Both are normalized into the same shape so the rest of the app doesn't care which endpoint was called.

#### The `newsService` Object
```js
const newsService = {
  async search(query = 'news', page = 0, options = {}) {
    const sortBy = options.sortBy || 'latest'
    const endpoint = sortBy === 'relevance' ? '/search' : '/search_by_date'
    // Algolia has TWO endpoints:
    // /search = sorted by relevance (AI-powered ranking)
    // /search_by_date = sorted by date (chronological)
    
    const data = await fetchJson(endpoint, {
      query,
      tags: 'story',     // Only fetch stories, not comments or jobs
      page,
      hitsPerPage: PAGE_SIZE
    })
    
    return {
      items: (data.hits || []).map(mapHitToArticle),
      hasMore: page + 1 < (data.nbPages || 0)
      // If current page +1 < total pages, there are more results
    }
  },
  
  async getItem(id) {
    const data = await fetchJson(`/items/${id}`)
    return mapItemToArticle(data)
  }
}

export default newsService
// Single export: one unified API client used throughout the app
```

